# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eslint
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] In this article, we provide an overview of modern web tooling, what kinds of tools are available and where you'll meet them in the lifecycle of web app development, and how to find help with individual tools.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Writing software for the web has become more sophisticated through the ages.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Although it is still entirely reasonable to write HTML, CSS, and JavaScript "by hand" there is now a wealth of tools that developers can use to speed up the process of building a website, or app.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] There are some extremely well-established tools that have become common "household names" amongst the development community, and new tools are being written and released every day to solve specific problems.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] You might even find yourself writing a piece of software to aid your own development process, to solve a specific problem that existing tools don't already seem to handle.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] It is easy to become overwhelmed by the sheer number of tools that can be included in a single project.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Equally, a single configuration file for a tool like webpack can be hundreds of lines long, most of which are magical incantations that seem to do the job but which only a master engineer will fully understand!
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] From time to time, even the most experienced of web developers get stuck on a tooling problem; it is possible to waste hours attempting to get a tooling pipeline working before even touching a single line of application code.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] If you have found yourself struggling in the past, then don't worry — you are not alone.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] In these articles, we won't answer every question about web tooling, but we will provide you with a useful starting point of understanding the fundamentals, which you can then build from.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] As with any complex topic, it is good to start small, and gradually work your way up to more advanced uses.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Today's modern developer tooling ecosystem is huge, so it's useful to have a broad idea of what main problems the tools are solving.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] If you jump on your favorite search engine and look for "front-end developer tools" you're going to hit a huge spectrum of results ranging from text editors, to browsers, to the type of pens you can use to take notes.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Though your choice of code editor is certainly a tooling choice, this series of articles will go beyond that, focusing on developer tools that help you produce web code more efficiently.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] We'll recommend a few particular tools and the following tutorials will show you how to use them.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] They are tools that are popular and standard at the time of writing.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This does not preclude you from using other tools, if you are aware of their relative advantages.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Let's look at each one of these in more detail.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] The editor, operating system, and browser are all development environments.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] We will assume that you have already settled down with a choice you are most comfortable with.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] These are tools that make the code you write a little better.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This part of the tooling should be specific to your own development environment, though it's not uncommon for companies to have some kind of policy or pre-baked configuration available to install so that all their developers are using the same processes.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This includes anything that makes your development process easier for generating stable and reliable code.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Safety net tooling should also help you either prevent mistakes or correct mistakes automatically without having to build your code from scratch each time.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] A few very common safety net tool types you will find being used by developers are as follows.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] ESLint is the industry standard JavaScript linter — a highly configurable tool for catching potential syntax errors and encouraging "best practices" throughout your code.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Some companies and projects have also shared their ESLint configs.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] You can also find linting tools for other languages, such as stylelint.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Also known as **version control systems** (VCS), **source code control** is essential for backing work up and working in teams.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] A typical VCS involves having a local version of the code that you make changes to.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] You then "push" changes to a "master" version of the code inside a remote repository stored on a server somewhere.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] There is usually a way of controlling and coordinating what changes are made to the "master" copy of the code, and when, so a team of developers doesn't end up overwriting each other's work all the time.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Git is the source code control system that most people use these days.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] It is primarily accessed via the command line but can be accessed via friendly user interfaces.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] With your code in a git repository, you can push it to your own server instance, or use a hosted source control website such as GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] You can find more information about it at Git and GitHub.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Code formatters are somewhat related to linters, except that rather than point out errors in your code, they usually tend to make sure your code is formatted correctly, according to your style rules, ideally automatically fixing errors that they find.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Prettier is a very popular example of a code formatter, which we'll make use of later on in the module.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Type checkers are tools that help you write more reliable code by checking that your code is using the right types of data in the right places.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This prevents common classes of bugs such as accessing nonexistent properties, unexpected `undefined`, etc.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] TypeScript is the de facto standard type checker for JavaScript.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] It provides its own type annotation syntax and is somewhat a language in its own right, so we won't be covering it in this module.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This stage of your web app lifecycle typically allows you to code in either "future code" (such as the latest CSS or JavaScript features that might not have native support in browsers yet) or code using another language entirely, such as TypeScript.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Transformation tools will then generate browser-compatible code for you, to be used in production.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Generally, web development is thought of as three languages: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, and there are transformation tools for all of these languages.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] The option to write your code in an entirely different language and have it transformed into a web-compatible language.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Post-development tooling ensures that your software makes it to the web and continues to run.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This includes the deployment processes, testing frameworks, auditing tools, and more.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This stage of the development process is one that you want the least amount of active interaction with so that once it is configured, it runs mostly automatically, only popping up to say hello if something has gone wrong.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] These generally take the form of a tool that will automatically run tests against your code to make sure it is correct before you go any further (for example, when you attempt to push changes to a GitHub repo).
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This can include linting, but also more sophisticated procedures like unit tests, where you run part of your code, making sure they behave as they should.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Deployment systems allow you to get your website published, are available for both static and dynamic sites, and commonly tend to work alongside testing systems.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] For example, a typical toolchain will wait for you to push changes to a remote repo, run some tests to see if the changes are OK, and then if the tests pass, automatically deploy your app to a production site.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] GitHub Pages is nicely integrated with GitHub itself and is free for all public repos.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Other services, such as Netlify and Vercel, are also very popular, featuring generous free tier quotas, smooth deployment workflows, and GitHub integration.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] There's certainly an order in which the different tooling types apply in the development lifecycle, but rest assured that you don't *have* to have all of these in place to release a website.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] However, including some of these tools in your process will improve your own development experience and likely improve the overall quality of your code.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] It often takes some time for new developer tools to settle down in their complexity.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] One of the best-known tools, webpack, has a reputation for being overly complicated to work with, but in the latest major release, there was a huge push to simplify common usage so the configuration required is reduced down to an absolute minimum.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] There's definitely no silver bullet that will guarantee success with tools, but as your experience increases you'll find workflows that work *for you* or for your team and their projects.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Once all the kinks in the process are flattened out, your toolchain should be something you can forget about and it *should* just work.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Most tools tend to get written and released in isolation, so although there's almost certainly help available it's never in the same place or format.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] It can therefore be hard to find help with using a tool, or even to choose what tool to use.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] The knowledge about which are the best tools to use is a bit tribal, meaning that if you aren't already in the web community, it is hard to find out exactly which ones to go for!
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This is one reason we wrote this series of articles, to hopefully provide that first step that is hard to find otherwise.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] When you've chosen a tool to use, the first port of call should be the tool project homepage.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This could be a full-blown website or it might be a single readme document in a code repository.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] The date-fns docs for example are pretty good, complete, and easy to follow.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Some documentation however can be rather technical and academic and not a good fit for your learning needs.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Instead, you might want to find some dedicated tutorials on getting started with particular types of tools.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] A great starting place is to search websites like CSS Tricks, Dev, freeCodeCamp, and Smashing Magazine, as they're tailored to the web development industry.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Again, you'll probably go through several different tools as you search for the right ones for you, trying them out to see if they make sense, are well-supported, and do what you want them to do.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] This is fine — it is all good for learning, and the road will get smoother as you get more experience.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] That rounds off our gentle introduction to the topic of client-side web tooling, from a high level.
[src:eslint/client-side-tools-overview] Next up we will look at package managers.
[src:eslint/eslint] Both JSLint and JSHint were lacking the ability to create additional rules for code quality and coding style.
[src:eslint/eslint] After contributing to JSHint, Zakas decided to create a new linting tool in June 2013, ESLint (originally called JSCheck, but renamed a month later), where all rules are configurable, and additional rules can be defined or loaded at run-time.
[src:eslint/eslint] In April 2016, the ESLint project joined the jQuery Foundation.
[src:eslint/eslint] Later that year, jQuery Foundation merged with Dojo Foundation to become JS Foundation as a Linux Foundation project.
[src:eslint/eslint] In October 2017, the ESLint project became a "Graduate Project" of the JS Foundation through its mentorship program.
[src:eslint/eslint] As of March 2019, ESLint is part of the OpenJS Foundation, following a merge between the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation.
[src:eslint/eslint] JetBrains provides integrated support for ESLint in their WebStorm code editor, which runs the ESLint software as configured for the current text file, and displays any warnings near the offending lines of code in the editor.
[src:eslint/eslint] Since 2016, the Vue.js project provides an ESLint plugin to automatically validate use of Vue.js templates and other features.
[src:eslint/eslint] Since 2018, this plugin is also promoted in the wizard for creating new Vue.js projects.
[src:eslint/eslint] In October 2018, the React project (developed by Facebook) published an official ESLint plugin to help enforce their coding rules.
[src:eslint/eslint] As of 2025, ESLint is the most commonly used JavaScript linter and is being downloaded over 43,000,000 times per week.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Johnson, a computer scientist at Bell Labs, came up with the term "lint" in 1978 while debugging the yacc grammar he was writing for C and dealing with portability issues stemming from porting Unix to a 32-bit machine.
[src:eslint/lint-software] The term was borrowed from lint, the tiny bits of fiber and fluff shed by clothing, as the command he wrote would act like a lint trap in a clothes dryer, capturing waste fibers while leaving whole fabrics intact.
[src:eslint/lint-software] The lint program was released outside of Bell Labs in Unix V7, in 1979.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Over the years, different versions of lint have been developed for many C and C++ compilers, and while modern-day compilers have lint-like functions, static analysis tools have also advanced their capabilities.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Today linting refers to checking code for formatting and stylistic errors and can be seen in tools such as PHP CodeSniffer (PHP), ESLint (JavaScript), Stylelint (CSS), Pylint (Python), RuboCop (Ruby) and golint (Go).
[src:eslint/lint-software] Many linting tools also perform static analysis.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Although today "linting" refers to style and formatting analysis of code, the successors of the original Lint continue its tradition by performing static program analysis.
[src:eslint/lint-software] The analysis performed by Lint-like tools can also be performed by an optimizing compiler, which aims to generate faster code.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Even though modern compilers have evolved to include many of lint's historical functions, lint-like tools have also evolved to detect an even wider variety of suspicious constructs.
[src:eslint/lint-software] These include "warnings about syntax errors, uses of undeclared variables, calls to deprecated functions, spacing and formatting conventions, misuse of scope, implicit fallthrough in switch statements, missing license headers, [and]...dangerous language features".
[src:eslint/lint-software] Lint-like tools are especially useful for dynamically typed languages like JavaScript and Python.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Lint-like tools generally perform static analysis of source code.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Lint-like tools have also been developed for other aspects of software development, such as enforcing grammar and style guides for given language source code.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Some tools (such as ESLint) also allow rules to be auto-fixable: a rule definition can also come with the definition of a transform that resolves the warning.
[src:eslint/lint-software] Rules about style are especially likely to come with an auto-fix.
[src:eslint/lint-software] If the linter is run in "fix all" mode on a file that triggers only rules about formatting, the linter will act just like a formatter.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Maintaining a consistent style across a codebase can improve readability and ease of software maintenance.
[src:eslint/programming-style] It allows developers to quickly understand code written by others and reduces the likelihood of errors during modifications.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Adhering to standardized coding guidelines ensures that teams follow a uniform approach, making the codebase easier to manage and scale.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Many organizations and open-source projects adopt specific coding standards to facilitate collaboration and reduce cognitive load.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Style guidelines can be formalized in documents known as **coding conventions**, which dictate specific formatting and naming rules.
[src:eslint/programming-style] These conventions may be prescribed by official standards for a programming language or developed internally within a team or project.
[src:eslint/programming-style] For example, Python's PEP 8 is a widely recognized style guide that outlines best practices for writing Python code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] In contrast, languages like C or Java may have industry standards that are either formally documented or adhered to by convention.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Adherence to coding style can be enforced through automated tools, known as linters, which format code according to predefined guidelines.
[src:eslint/programming-style] These linting tools reduce the manual effort required to maintain style consistency, allowing programmers to focus on logic and functionality.
[src:eslint/programming-style] For instance, tools such as CSSLint for CSS, Black for Python, clang-format for C++, PHP-CS-Fixer for PHP, ESLint for JavaScript, automatically reformat code to comply with specified coding style standards.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Indentation style can assist a reader in various ways including: identifying control flow and blocks of code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] In some programming languages, indentation is used to delimit blocks of code and therefore is not matter of style.
[src:eslint/programming-style] In languages that ignore whitespace, indentation can affect readability.
[src:eslint/programming-style] The ModuLiq Zero Indentation Style groups by empty line rather than indenting.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Lua does not use the traditional curly braces or parentheses; rather, the expression in a conditional statement must be followed by `then`, and the block must be closed with `end`.
[src:eslint/programming-style] `and`, `or`, and `not` function as logical operators.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Python relies on the *off-side rule*, using indenting to indicate and implement control structure, thus eliminating the need for bracketing (i.e., `{` and `}`).
[src:eslint/programming-style] However, copying and pasting indented code can cause problems, because the indent level of the pasted code may not be the same as the indent level of the target line.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Such reformatting by hand is tedious and error prone, but some text editors and integrated development environments (IDEs) have features to do it automatically.
[src:eslint/programming-style] There are also problems when indented code is rendered unusable when posted on a forum or web page that removes whitespace, though this problem can be avoided where it is possible to enclose code in whitespace-preserving tags such as "<pre> ... </pre>" (for HTML), "[code]" ...
[src:eslint/programming-style] Python starts a block with a colon (`:`).
[src:eslint/programming-style] Python programmers tend to follow a commonly agreed style guide known as PEP8.
[src:eslint/programming-style] There are tools designed to automate PEP8 compliance.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Haskell, like Python, has the *off-side rule*.
[src:eslint/programming-style] It has a two-dimension syntax where indenting is meaningful to define blocks (although, an alternate syntax uses curly braces and semicolons).
[src:eslint/programming-style] Haskell is a declarative language, there are statements, but declarations within a Haskell script.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Haskell encourages the use of literate programming, where extended text explains the genesis of the code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] In literate Haskell scripts (named with the `lhs` extension), everything is a comment except blocks marked as code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] The program can be written in LaTeX, in such case the `code` environment marks what is code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Also, each active code paragraph can be marked by preceding and ending it with an empty line, and starting each line of code with a greater than sign and a space.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Some programmers consider it valuable to align similar elements vertically (as tabular, in columns), citing that it can make typo-generated bugs more obvious.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Unlike the unaligned code, the aligned code implies that the search and replace values are related since they have corresponding elements.
[src:eslint/programming-style] As there is one more value for search than replacement, if this is a bug, it is more likely to be spotted via visual inspection.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Maintaining alignment can be alleviated by a tool that provides support (i.e. for elastic tabstops), although that creates a reliance on such tools.
[src:eslint/programming-style] A free-format language ignores whitespace characters: spaces, tabs and new lines so the programmer is free to style the code in different ways without affecting the meaning of the code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Generally, the programmer uses style that is considered to enhance readability.
[src:eslint/programming-style] The two code snippets below are the same logically, but differ in whitespace.
[src:eslint/programming-style] The use of tabs for whitespace is debatable.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Alignment issues arise due to differing tab stops in different environments and mixed use of tabs and spaces.
[src:eslint/programming-style] As an example, one programmer prefers tab stops of four and has their toolset configured this way, and uses these to format their code.
[src:eslint/programming-style] Another programmer prefers tab stops of eight, and their toolset is configured this way.
[src:eslint/programming-style] When someone else examines the original person's code, they may well find it difficult to read.
[src:eslint/programming-style] One widely used solution to this issue may involve forbidding the use of tabs for alignment or rules on how tab stops must be set.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The term is usually applied to analysis performed by an automated tool, with human analysis typically being called "program understanding", program comprehension, or code review.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] In the last of these, software inspection and software walkthroughs are also used.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] In most cases the analysis is performed on some version of a program's source code, and, in other cases, on some form of its object code.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The discipline of static analysis should not be confused with linting, which is the process of checking for coding style mistakes.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The sophistication of the analysis performed by tools varies from those that only consider the behaviour of individual statements and declarations, to those that include the complete source code of a program in their analysis.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The uses of the information obtained from the analysis vary from highlighting possible coding errors (e.g., the lint tool) to formal methods that mathematically prove properties about a given program (e.g., its behaviour matches that of its specification).
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Software metrics and reverse engineering can be described as forms of static analysis.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Deriving software metrics and static analysis are increasingly deployed together, especially in creation of embedded systems, by defining so-called *software quality objectives*.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] A growing commercial use of static analysis is in the verification of properties of software used in safety-critical computer systems and locating potentially vulnerable code.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Nuclear software: In the UK the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) recommends the use of static analysis on reactor protection systems.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Aviation software (in combination with dynamic analysis).
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Automotive & Machines (functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ISO 26262, section 8).
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] A study in 2012 by VDC Research reported that 28.7% of the embedded software engineers surveyed use static analysis tools and 39.7% expect to use them within 2 years.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] A study from 2010 found that 60% of the interviewed developers in European research projects made at least use of their basic IDE built-in static analyzers.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] However, only about 10% employed an additional other (and perhaps more advanced) analysis tool.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] In the application security industry the name static application security testing (SAST) is also used.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] SAST is an important part of Security Development Lifecycles (SDLs) such as the SDL defined by Microsoft and a common practice in software companies.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The OMG (Object Management Group) published a study regarding the types of software analysis required for software quality measurement and assessment.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] This document on "How to Deliver Resilient, Secure, Efficient, and Easily Changed IT Systems in Line with CISQ Recommendations" describes three levels of software analysis.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes place within a specific program or subroutine, without connecting to the context of that program.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the interactions between unit programs, but without being limited to one specific technology or programming language.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] A further level of software analysis can be defined.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the business/mission layer terms, rules and processes that are implemented within the software system for its operation as part of enterprise or program/mission layer activities.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] These elements are implemented without being limited to one specific technology or programming language and in many cases are distributed across multiple languages, but are statically extracted and analyzed for system understanding for mission assurance.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Many static analysis tools use intermediate representations of programs to examine the structure of source code without executing the program.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] For this purpose, abstract syntax trees (ASTs) are commonly used, since they provide a structured representation of a program's syntactic elements.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Formal methods is the term applied to the analysis of software (and computer hardware) whose results are obtained purely through the use of rigorous mathematical methods.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The mathematical techniques used include denotational semantics, axiomatic semantics, operational semantics, and abstract interpretation.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] This result dates from the works of Church, Gödel and Turing in the 1930s (see: Halting problem and Rice's theorem).
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] As with many undecidable questions, one can still attempt to give useful approximate solutions.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] Data-driven static analysis leverages extensive codebases to infer coding rules and improve the accuracy of the analysis.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] For instance, one can use all Java open-source packages available on GitHub to learn good analysis strategies.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] The rule inference can use machine learning techniques.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] It is also possible to learn from a large amount of past fixes and warnings.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] For certain types of warnings, it is possible to design and implement automated remediation techniques.
[src:eslint/static-program-analysis] For example, Logozzo and Ball have proposed automated remediations for C# *cccheck*.
[src:eslint/using-classes] JavaScript is a prototype-based language — an object's behaviors are specified by its own properties and its prototype's properties.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, with the addition of classes, the creation of hierarchies of objects and the inheritance of properties and their values are much more in line with other object-oriented languages such as Java.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In this section, we will demonstrate how objects can be created from classes.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In many other languages, *classes*, or constructors, are clearly distinguished from *objects*, or instances.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In JavaScript, classes are mainly an abstraction over the existing prototypical inheritance mechanism — all patterns are convertible to prototype-based inheritance.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Classes themselves are normal JavaScript values as well, and have their own prototype chains.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In fact, most plain JavaScript functions can be used as constructors — you use the `new` operator with a constructor function to create a new object.
[src:eslint/using-classes] We will be playing with the well-abstracted class model in this tutorial, and discuss what semantics classes offer.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If you want to dive deep into the underlying prototype system, you can read the Inheritance and the prototype chain guide.
[src:eslint/using-classes] This chapter assumes that you are already somewhat familiar with JavaScript and that you have used ordinary objects.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If you have some hands-on experience with JavaScript, or have followed along with the guide, you probably have already used classes, even if you haven't created one.
[src:eslint/using-classes] On the first line, we created an instance of the class `Date`, and called it `bigDay`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] On the second line, we called a method `toLocaleDateString()` on the `bigDay` instance, which returns a string.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Then, we compared two numbers: one returned from the `getTime()` method, the other directly called from the `Date` class *itself*, as `Date.now()`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] `Date` is a built-in class of JavaScript.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Classes are usually created with *class declarations*.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Within a class body, there are a range of features available.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If you came from a pre-ES6 world, you may be more familiar with using functions as constructors.
[src:eslint/using-classes] After a class has been declared, you can create instances of it using the `new` operator.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Typical function constructors can both be constructed with `new` and called without `new`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, attempting to "call" a class without `new` will result in an error.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Unlike function declarations, class declarations are not hoisted (or, in some interpretations, hoisted but with the temporal dead zone restriction), which means you cannot use a class before it is declared.
[src:eslint/using-classes] This behavior is similar to variables declared with `let` and `const`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Similar to functions, class declarations also have their expression counterparts.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Class expressions can have names as well.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The expression's name is only visible to the class's body.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Perhaps the most important job of a class is to act as a "factory" for objects.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For example, when we use the `Date` constructor, we expect it to give a new object which represents the date data we passed in — which we can then manipulate with other methods the instance exposes.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In classes, the instance creation is done by the constructor.
[src:eslint/using-classes] As an example, we would create a class called `Color`, which represents a specific color.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Users create colors through passing in an RGB triplet.
[src:eslint/using-classes] You have successfully created a `Color` instance, and the instance has a `values` property, which is an array of the RGB values you passed in.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Each time you call `new`, a different instance is created.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Within a class constructor, the value of `this` points to the newly created instance.
[src:eslint/using-classes] You can assign properties to it, or read existing properties (especially methods — which we will cover next).
[src:eslint/using-classes] The `this` value will be automatically returned as the result of `new`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] You are advised to not return any value from the constructor — because if you return a non-primitive value, it will become the value of the `new` expression, and the value of `this` is dropped.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If a class only has a constructor, it is not much different from a `createX` factory function which just creates plain objects.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, the power of classes is that they can be used as "templates" which automatically assign methods to instances.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For example, for `Date` instances, you can use a range of methods to get different information from a single date value, such as the year, month, day of the week, etc.
[src:eslint/using-classes] You can also set those values through the `setX` counterparts like `setFullYear`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For our own `Color` class, we can add a method called `getRed` which returns the red value of the color.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, a problem is that this creates a new function every time a `Color` instance is created, even when they all do the same thing!
[src:eslint/using-classes] In contrast, if you use a method, it will be shared between all instances.
[src:eslint/using-classes] A function can be shared between all instances, but still have its behavior differ when different instances call it, because the value of `this` is different.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If you are curious *where* this method is stored in — it's defined on the prototype of all instances, or `Color.prototype`, which is explained in more detail in Inheritance and the prototype chain.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Similarly, we can create a new method called `setRed`, which sets the red value of the color.
[src:eslint/using-classes] You might be wondering: why do we want to go to the trouble of using `getRed` and `setRed` methods, when we can directly access the `values` array on the instance?
[src:eslint/using-classes] There is a philosophy in object-oriented programming called "encapsulation".
[src:eslint/using-classes] This means you should not access the underlying implementation of an object, but instead use well-abstracted methods to interact with it.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The user assumption that `values` means the RGB value suddenly collapses, and it may cause their logic to break.
[src:eslint/using-classes] So, if you are an implementor of a class, you would want to hide the internal data structure of your instance from your user, both to keep the API clean and to prevent the user's code from breaking when you do some "harmless refactors".
[src:eslint/using-classes] In classes, this is done through *private fields*.
[src:eslint/using-classes] A private field is an identifier prefixed with `#` (the hash symbol).
[src:eslint/using-classes] The hash is an integral part of the field's name, which means a private field can never have name clash with a public field or method.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In order to refer to a private field anywhere in the class, you must *declare* it in the class body (you can't create a private element on the fly).
[src:eslint/using-classes] Apart from this, a private field is pretty much equivalent to a normal property.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Accessing private fields outside the class is an early syntax error.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The language can guard against this because `#privateField` is a special syntax, so it can do some static analysis and find all usage of private fields before even evaluating the code.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Private fields in JavaScript are *hard private*: if the class does not implement methods that expose these private fields, there's absolutely no mechanism to retrieve them from outside the class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] This means you are safe to do any refactors to your class's private fields, as long as the behavior of exposed methods stay the same.
[src:eslint/using-classes] After we've made the `values` field private, we can add some more logic in the `getRed` and `setRed` methods, instead of making them simple pass-through methods.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If we leave the `values` property exposed, our users can easily circumvent that check by assigning to `values[0]` directly, and create invalid colors.
[src:eslint/using-classes] But with a well-encapsulated API, we can make our code more robust and prevent logic errors downstream.
[src:eslint/using-classes] A class method can read the private fields of other instances, as long as they belong to the same class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, if `anotherColor` is not a Color instance, `#values` won't exist.
[src:eslint/using-classes] (Even if another class has an identically named `#values` private field, it's not referring to the same thing and cannot be accessed here.) Accessing a nonexistent private element throws an error instead of returning `undefined` like normal properties do.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If you don't know if a private field exists on an object and you wish to access it without using `try`/`catch` to handle the error, you can use the `in` operator.
[src:eslint/using-classes] There are some limitations in using private elements: the same name can't be declared twice in a single class, and they can't be deleted.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Methods, getters, and setters can be private as well.
[src:eslint/using-classes] They're useful when you have something complex that the class needs to do internally but no other part of the code should be allowed to call.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For example, imagine creating HTML custom elements that should do something somewhat complicated when clicked/tapped/otherwise activated.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Furthermore, the somewhat complicated things that happen when the element is clicked should be restricted to this class, because no other part of the JavaScript will (or should) ever access it.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In this case, pretty much every field and method is private to the class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Thus, it presents an interface to the rest of the code that's essentially just like a built-in HTML element.
[src:eslint/using-classes] No other part of the program has the power to affect any of the internals of `Counter`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] `color.getRed()` and `color.setRed()` allow us to read and write to the red value of a color.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If you come from languages like Java, you will be very familiar with this pattern.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, using methods to simply access a property is still somewhat unergonomic in JavaScript.
[src:eslint/using-classes] *Accessor fields* allow us to manipulate something as if it is an "actual property".
[src:eslint/using-classes] It looks as if the object has a property called `red` — but actually, no such property exists on the instance!
[src:eslint/using-classes] There are only two methods, but they are prefixed with `get` and `set`, which allows them to be manipulated as if they were properties.
[src:eslint/using-classes] If a field only has a getter but no setter, it will be effectively read-only.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In strict mode, the `red.red = 0` line will throw a type error: "Cannot set property red of #<Color> which has only a getter".
[src:eslint/using-classes] In non-strict mode, the assignment is silently ignored.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Private fields also have their public counterparts, which allow every instance to have a property.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Fields are usually designed to be independent of the constructor's parameters.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Public fields are almost equivalent to assigning a property to `this`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] With the `Date` example, we have also encountered the `Date.now()` method, which returns the current date.
[src:eslint/using-classes] This method does not belong to any date instance — it belongs to the class itself.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, it's put on the `Date` class instead of being exposed as a global `DateNow()` function, because it's mostly useful when dealing with date instances.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Everything also has private counterparts.
[src:eslint/using-classes] There is also a special construct called a *static initialization block*, which is a block of code that runs when the class is first loaded.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Static initialization blocks are almost equivalent to immediately executing some code after a class has been declared.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The only difference is that they have access to static private elements.
[src:eslint/using-classes] A key feature that classes bring about (in addition to ergonomic encapsulation with private fields) is *inheritance*, which means one object can "borrow" a large part of another object's behaviors, while overriding or enhancing certain parts with its own logic.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For example, suppose our `Color` class now needs to support transparency.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, this means every instance — even the vast majority which aren't transparent (those with an alpha value of 1) — will have to have the extra alpha value, which is not very elegant.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Plus, if the features keep growing, our `Color` class will become very bloated and hard to maintain.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Instead, in object-oriented programming, we would create a *derived class*.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The derived class has access to all public properties of the parent class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In JavaScript, derived classes are declared with an `extends` clause, which indicates the class it extends from.
[src:eslint/using-classes] There are a few things that have immediately come to attention.
[src:eslint/using-classes] First is that in the constructor, we are calling `super(r, g, b)`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] It is a language requirement to call `super()` before accessing `this`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The `super()` call calls the parent class's constructor to initialize `this` — here it's roughly equivalent to `this = new Color(r, g, b)`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] You can have code before `super()`, but you cannot access `this` before `super()` — the language prevents you from accessing the uninitialized `this`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] After the parent class is done with modifying `this`, the derived class can do its own logic.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Here we added a private field called `#alpha`, and also provided a pair of getter/setters to interact with them.
[src:eslint/using-classes] A derived class inherits all methods from its parent.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Derived classes can also override methods from the parent class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For example, all classes implicitly inherit the `Object` class, which defines some basic methods like `toString()`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Within derived classes, you can access the parent class's methods by using `super`.
[src:eslint/using-classes] This allows you to build enhancement methods and avoid code duplication.
[src:eslint/using-classes] When you use `extends`, the static methods inherit from each other as well, so you can also override or enhance them.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Derived classes don't have access to the parent class's private fields — this is another key aspect to JavaScript private fields being "hard private".
[src:eslint/using-classes] Private fields are scoped to the class body itself and do not grant access to *any* outside code.
[src:eslint/using-classes] This prevents problems in multiple inheritance like the diamond problem.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, due to the dynamic nature of JavaScript, it's still possible to achieve the effect of multiple inheritance through class composition and mixins.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Instances of derived classes are also instances of the base class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] The guide has been pragmatic so far: we are focusing on *how* classes can be used, but there's one question unanswered: *why* would one use a class?
[src:eslint/using-classes] Classes introduce a *paradigm*, or a way to organize your code.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Classes are the foundations of object-oriented programming, which is built on concepts like inheritance and polymorphism (especially *subtype polymorphism*).
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, many people are philosophically against certain OOP practices and don't use classes as a result.
[src:eslint/using-classes] For example, one thing that makes `Date` objects infamous is that they're *mutable*.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Mutability and internal state are important aspects of object-oriented programming, but often make code hard to reason with — because any seemingly innocent operation may have unexpected side effects and change the behavior in other parts of the program.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In order to reuse code, we usually resort to extending classes, which can create big hierarchies of inheritance patterns.
[src:eslint/using-classes] However, it is often hard to describe inheritance cleanly when one class can only extend one other class.
[src:eslint/using-classes] Often, we want the behavior of multiple classes.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In Java, this is done through interfaces; in JavaScript, it can be done through mixins.
[src:eslint/using-classes] But at the end of the day, it's still not very convenient.
[src:eslint/using-classes] On the brighter side, classes are a very powerful way to organize our code on a higher level.
[src:eslint/using-classes] But with classes, we can congregate them all under the `Color` namespace, which improves readability.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In addition, the introduction of private fields allows us to hide certain data from downstream users, creating a clean API.
[src:eslint/using-classes] In general, you should consider using classes when you want to create objects that store their own internal data and expose a lot of behavior.
[src:eslint/using-classes] JavaScript offers the mechanism to organize your code in a canonical object-oriented way, but whether and how to use it is entirely up to the programmer's discretion.
